<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-01-30T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-01-30T14:00:00-05:00" n="135" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d135">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3696: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China (<persName corresp="#p_JNT1" type="to">Johnson</persName>)</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-01-30T14:00:00-05:00">January 30, 1932—2
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>36. Your 148, January 29, 5 p.m., last paragraph. The Department feels
                            that, for the present at least, authorities of the International
                            Settlement and the defense forces at Shanghai should confine their
                            activities strictly to the maintenance of peace and order in the
                            Settlement and other areas in which they have hitherto thus
                            functioned.</p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_SHL1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>